snippet.textDisplay: Excellent analysis of the storytelling problems in Kennedy's Star Wars films, but I do take issue with their love of TFA.  All of the problems of this trilogy flow from The Force Awakens- a "mystery box" setup with no real answers or planned direction, a structural retread that didn't spawn a fascinating new premise.  Everything is left dangling because there was no vision on the answers, just questions.  Rian Johnson gave us the only possible answer for why Luke had abandoned everyone and everything he loved, and did the best anyone could've done with the setup of TFA, which had not been thought through.  Now, Abrams is trying to undo everything in an improvised story that makes the trilogy seem schizophrenic.  But all of the trilogy's problems stem from the root - The Force Awakens.
snippet.textOriginal: Excellent analysis of the storytelling problems in Kennedy's Star Wars films, but I do take issue with their love of TFA. snippet.textDisplay: Something that they’re not mentioning, in regards to the MCU vs Star Wars, is that the MCU isn’t trying to make direct sequels.  Each movie is very much it’s own thing and only one or 2 plot points in each movie actually carry over to the next movie.  Contradictory to that, the Star Wars trilogies are direct continuations, so there is not as much room for each director to bring their own style.  MCU movies can explore various aspects of what it means to be a hero and can jump from tone to tone.  The Star Wars trilogy cant, it needs to feel cohesive.  It would be like if MCU gave Infinity War and Endgame to 2 different directors.  Those movies work because they are a direct continuation and were worked on by the exact same creative team.  They were written at the same time and filmed back to back.  I think that’s where Star Wars went wrong.  They needed to write all 3 movies before they went and shot them.  And ideally have them all directed by the same director, maybe Abrams but based on the reviews of TROS maybe not haha

snippet.textDisplay: I hate The Last Jedi. I found it completely assassinated Luke's story, accomplishments, character ... I like Star Wars, I like Science Fiction ... I never went into the EU. I watched series like Clone Wars and Rebels. Luke Skywalker was my hero in the original trilogy. The Last Jedi was about killing the past. Which as a local historian I completely do not subscribe too. If you want to be subverted, kill the past etc. do not do it in a 'Skywalker saga' movie. Just make a new Star Wars movie with new characters. If you make a 'Skywalker saga' movie you respect the history and heritage of what came before. The Last Jedi did not do that. I can understand if you are for or against The Last Jedi but one can't deny it was a divisive film. If something was divisive, I'd rather choose something uniting. There are these websites like IO9 where I really get the feeling that I must be like some guy who kills younglings for not liking The Last Jedi. They seem to say that if you dislike The Last Jedi you are some sort of womenhating andwhatnot monster. I take offense to that. My hate of The Last Jedi has nothing to do with gender, wokeness or whatever. I consider myself to be a nuanced 35yo guy from Europe. I really hate it when they group me with womenhaters etc. Is it than not allowed to have criticisms about The Last Jedi? Must we all slavishly like it? If you liked it, fine! But don't go telling me I have to like it too and that everything I say is worthless. I do not believe in killing the past. Where is your future going to go if you don't take the past into account? Whatever Dan and Roth said about The Last Jedi, The Rise of Skywalker etc. I like that they are nuanced, shades of grey ... They are atleast open to other viewpoints. They seem like people with respect to others. I haven't seen The Rise of Skywalker yet but I found this non-spoiler review to be worth the watch. I respect Dan's and Roth's opinion.

snippet.textDisplay:
I've said for a while now TFA should have been Ep 8 and TLJ should have been Ep 9. Johnson ended with the broom kid being the hopeful future of the Force. Ep 7 should have been a re-introduction to the older characters while introducing us to the new, while also showing Luke teaching the new Jedi in response to the remnants of the Empire starting to reform as the First Order. At the same time Leia experiences a fundamental difference of philosophy with Holdo and the New Republic about developing a stronger military. Ep 7 could have ended with a disillusioned Luke disappearing but leaving a clue to his destination for Leia while she secretly forms the Resistance.


It's disappointing we only got two really good Saga movies before it began to fall apart with Return Of The Jedi. The best Star Wars movie since Empire is Rogue One because it was completely faithful and respectful to the OT (far more than the prequels) while telling a new story with new characters we knew nothing about.
